    {
      "id": "_60q30c1g60o30e1i60o4ac1g60rj8gpl88rj2c1h84s34h9g60s30c1g60o30c1g64o3gc1g6l33ahi38cok8gpg64o30c1g60o30c1g60o30c1g60o32c1g60o30c1g84o48c9h84o36gq1610k8ghk88s4aci16d132d1l6t2k8dho6sqg",
      "title": "AI Hardware Options For ironsail.ai",
      "start": "2026-04-03T12:15:00-04:00",
      "startEpoch": 1775232900,
      "startLocal": "12:15 PM",
      "end": "2026-04-03T12:35:00-04:00",
      "endLocal": "12:35 PM",
      "location": "Microsoft Teams Meeting",
      "description": "** Added important updated from Philip D'Agostino **\n\nHello Philip and Conrad,\n\nI hope this note finds you well. Please join this call<https://teams.microsoft.com/meet/22664120794612?p=4ZKLA7q1N2amG6OgLP> to evaluate options for ironsail.ai<https://ironsail.ai/>. I included below all relevant correspondence for your reference.\n\nJoin the meeting now<https://teams.microsoft.com/meet/22664120794612?p=4ZKLA7q1N2amG6OgLP>\nMeeting ID: 226 641 207 946 12\nPasscode: yP9r3Tc2\nDial in by phone\n\n\u00b7   +1 469-998-7374,,208625757#<tel:+14699987374,,208625757> Dallas\n\n\u00b7   +1 323-673-4501,,208625757#<tel:+13236734501,208625757> Los Angeles\n\nFor organizers:\n\n\u00b7    Meeting options<https://teams.microsoft.com/meetingOptions/?organizerId=30fbc006-3a62-466e-a700-597793da122a&tenantId=e2fe0042-8583-4635-b9ee-d6e047d4b347&threadId=19_meeting_MDk2OTZkZWUtNDRmYy00ZWUzLThiYjktYjJmZjA1NGZiYTdh@thread.v2&messageId=0&language=en-US>\n\n\u00b7    Reset dial-in PIN<https://dialin.teams.microsoft.com/usp/pstnconferencing>\nPhone conference ID: 208 625 757#\nFind a local number<https://dialin.teams.microsoft.com/43118211-8073-4729-83db-cbdaf5ecfd22?id=208625757>\n\nLooking forward to speaking with you. Thank you.\n\nBesst Regards,\n\nMatt Budeir\nSuper Micro Computer, Inc.\n678 429-9286\nAccelerate Everything AI<https://www.supermicro.com/en/solutions/ai-deep-learning>\n\nFrom: robothor@ironsail.ai<mailto:robothor@ironsail.ai>\nSent: Wednesday, April 1, 2026 5:42 PM\nTo: Matt Budeir; Philip D'Agostino\nSubject: RE: Ironsail | HGX Rubin NVL8 \u2014 Meeting Request / Prototype Build For Ironsail Solutions\n\n\nMatt,\n\n\n\nGreat speaking with you today. NDA is signed \u2014 we're ready to move.\n\n\n\nPhilip and I consulted on the Super AI Station specs together and while it's an impressive machine, after working through our requirements we landed somewhere different. Our workload is specific:\n\nwe're running trillion-parameter MoE models \u2014 GLM-5, Kimi K2, DeepSeek-class \u2014 with multiple concurrent agentic instances serving business users simultaneously. The 252GB HBM3e on the Super AI Station, while powerful, would force us into quantization levels that compromise the reasoning quality we need.\n\n\n\nOur minimum viable target is 320GB aggregate VRAM across 4 GPUs \u2014 most likely an H100 configuration, though we're genuinely flexible on the exact variant. We're open to both SXM5 (NVLink, liquid cooled) and PCIe (air cooled, more modular) depending on what's available and what your contact can source. The PCIe variant actually has some appeal \u2014 it gives us flexibility to swap in next-generation cards like future Blackwell variants as they become available without being locked into a liquid cooling infrastructure.\n\n\n\nFor the full build, we'd be sourcing the complete stack \u2014 chassis, CPUs, RAM, NVMe storage, networking, and power \u2014 so this isn't just a GPU purchase. We'd want to spec the whole system correctly from the start and we'd welcome your guidance on what makes sense around whichever GPU path we take.\n\n\n\nYou mentioned earlier you could make an introduction to someone who could help us source these GPUs. We'd love to take you up on that.\n\n\n\nWe're ready to move and we want to get the right person involved so we can have a real conversation about availability, lead times, and pricing.\n\n\n\nLooking forward to it.\n\n\n\n\u2014 Philip D'Agostino & Robothor\n\nGenus OS / IronSail AI\n\n\n\n30 min with Philip (Matt Budeir) \u2013 April 1\n\n  *   Invited Robothor MHI mattb@supermicro.com<mailto:mattb@supermicro.com> Philip D'Agostino\n  *   Attachments 30 min with Philip (Matt Budeir)\n\nSummary\nIron Cell seeks hardware procurement for a private data center prototype with a focus on GPU sourcing and architecture support.\n\nData Center Prototype Scope\nIron Cell is building a private data center prototype to serve its internal AI token distribution, initially requiring less than 5 kilowatts of power but planning to scale to 30 megawatts. The prototype requires approximately 2 terabytes of RAM to serve large language models to around 20 concurrent users before securing further investment.\n\nGPU Hardware Procurement Strategy\nGPU allocation for the newer Reuben MBL8 is challenging due to hyperscaler priority, leading Iron Cell to consider starting with H100s or waiting if stacking is impossible. Iron Cell has an initial budget of approximately $100,000 for the setup, and a reseller is required since direct business is limited to larger enterprises.\n\nArchitecture Support and Compliance\nAn Nvidia expert will assist Iron Cell with system architecture and bill of materials identification, suggesting H-series GPUs for better cost efficiency than B-series. The software development entity, Iron Cell LLC, will be the buyer, and compliance vetting regarding GPU export and commercial address is required.\n\nNext steps\n\n  *   [Matt Budeir] Find Reseller Partner: Find proper channel partner for purchasing; they must handle business with smaller enterprises.\n  *   [Matt Budeir] Schedule Architect Call: Schedule follow-up call with Nvidia team; qualify requirements, determine Bill of Materials (BOM).\n  *   [Matt Budeir] Email SGX Pricing: Send email detailing SGX tower station pricing information.\n  *   [Matt Budeir] Send NDA: Send electronic NDA to Iron Cell LLC; ensure completion before technical discussions.\n\nDetails\n\n  *   Introduction and Business Overview: Philip D'Agostino, representing Iron Cell, discussed their diverse business holdings, including an AI orchestration platform, a web development team, and companies like an AI-first EMR system with a pharmacy marketplace, a telehealth company, and a real estate company. The discussion focused on their current venture into building a private data center to serve their businesses and eventually other entities. Philip D'Agostino described the data center as a business distribution center for their produced AI tokens.\n  *   Data Center Prototype and Expansion Plans: Philip D'Agostino outlined the plan to build a private data center prototype, initially focusing on setting up an agent orchestration system with a local large language model (LLM) server to serve their existing businesses. They estimated the initial prototype would require a power capacity under five kilowatts, with a goal to expand to at least 30 megawatts over time. The prototype needs approximately two terabytes of RAM to quickly serve LLMs to multiple users, targeting about 20 concurrent sessions for initial functionality before securing further investment.\n  *   GPU Requirements and Hardware Scalability: The discussion focused on the necessary GPU hardware, noting that the allocation for the newer Reuben MBL8 is currently a problem due to hyperscaler priority. Philip D'Agostino expressed interest in a scalable stack, suggesting starting with H100s and then integrating Reuben units, but stated they would wait for Reuben if stacking was not an option. Matt Budeir noted that they might be able to source relatively inexpensive refurbished hardware for the initial purchase, which Philip D'Agostino confirmed they are funding themself initially with a budget of around $100,000 to acquire the initial setup before adding more GPUs and nodes.\n  *   Reseller and Architecture Support:  Matt Budeir informed Philip D'Agostino that direct business is typically only conducted with larger enterprises, so a proper channel partner or reseller would be required for the purchase. Philip D'Agostino stated they have only used cloud services previously and are seeking early access to modern components for this first venture into hardware.  Matt Budeir offered to bring in an Nvidia expert to help architect the system and identify the necessary bill of materials, noting that H-series GPUs might be more cost-efficient than B-series.\n  *   Proposed Location and Current Hosting: Philip D'Agostino identified Texas as the preferred location for the data center build-out, with multiple properties in mind, but noted a Florida property with solar coverage could temporarily host the prototype. Regarding current hosting, Philip D'Agostino anticipates connecting the prototype with their existing AWS and Cloudflare infrastructure and serving the business privately, planning to keep it closed",
